Including GitHub Actions To Your Rust Projects
Tutorial

Including GitHub Actions To Your Rust Projects

7 steps

In this very short tutorial, you will learn an essential part in Rust development including continuous integrations (CI) on your Rust projects using GitHub Actions!

Let's start learning!

For technical help on the StackUp platform & tutorial-related questions, join our Discord, to ask your question.
Join us on Discord

Helpful prior knowledge

  • Recommended to have finished Rust Basics.
  • A working Rust installation. For instructions, head to https://rustup.rs/ and follow the platform-specific instructions.
  • Recommended to know Git and GitHub. For a tutorial, head to Version Control Basics with Git and GitHub. Git must be installed and configured before doing this tutorial.

Learning Outcomes

You will be able to:

  • Explain basic GitHub Actions or CI workflows in Rust projects.
  • Write GitHub Workflow YAML configuration specifically for Rust projects.
  • Build, check formatting, and run tests on your Rust projects with GitHub Actions.

Tutorial Steps

Total steps: 7

  • Step 1: Writing A Dummy Project

    Once Rust is installed (see prerequisites), run the following command on your terminal.

    cargo new dummy-rust-project

    The version of Rust in this tutorial is 1.86 with Rust edition 2024. Ensure that you have at least version 1.86.

    This will create a new Rust project with a root directory called dummy-rust-project. Head to the dummy-rust-project directory. Run the following command.

    cargo run

    This should give an output on the terminal "Hello, world!". If so, this means the project was generated correctly.

    Head to the src directory and create a new file called lib.rs. Write the following code to lib.rs.

    pub fn hello(name: &str) -> String {
    let hello_string = format!("Hello, {}!", name);
    hello_string
}

pub fn goodbye(name: &str) -> String {
    let goodbye_string = format!("Goodbye, {}!", name);
    goodbye_string
}
    Rust

    Open your main.rs file and replace the contents with the following code.

    use dummy_rust_project::hello;

fn main() {
    let say_hello = hello("Stackie");
    println!("{}", say_hello);
}
    Rust

    On your terminal, run the following command.

    cargo run

    This should output "Hello, Stackie!" on your terminal. Now that we have at least some code to experiment, let's head over to the next step.

  • Step 2: Writing Our Workflow Manually

    If you are not yet familiar with DevOps yet with GitHub and GitHub Actions, head over to CI/CD with GitHub. The linked tutorial might need you to head to previous tutorials. Don't worry, we recommended it so you can skim and familiarise with what a GitHub workflow looks like.

    In this step, you are going to write on manually without the GitHub web interface. This helps you familiarise with how to write workflows manually and the YAML format.

    GitHub workflow files are configuration files that define a sequence of commands for building, testing, and deploying projects, including websites. The format is in YAML format, a friendly data-serialization language as described in their website.

    Create a new directory called .github. Ensure this has a period before the directory name. This implies a "hidden" directory.

    Head to the .github directory and create a new directory called workflows. Inside the workflows directory, create a file called ci.yml. Write the following workflow configuration to your ci.yml.

    name: CI for Dummy Rust Project

on: ["push", "pull_request"]

env:
  CARGO_TERM_COLOR: always

jobs:
  build:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    steps:
    - name: Checkout
      uses: actions/checkout@v4
    - name: Install Rustup and Rust
      run: |
        sudo apt update
        sudo apt upgrade -y
        sudo apt install rustup -y
        rustup install stable
    - name: Run Rust binary
      run: |
        cargo run
    YAML

    GitHub has more in-depth documentation about GitHub workflows. If you want to see their full documentation, click this link.

    The screenshot below should show what your file and directory structure now looks like for the "dummy rust project".

    Now, head to https://github.com and login to your GitHub account. If you don't have a GitHub account, please sign up and create one. Once logged in, create a new repository called dummy-rust-project.

    Run the following commands on your terminal. You need to configure your Git credentials first before running the following commands.

    git add -A
git commit -m 'initial commit'

    Replace "yourusername" with your GitHub username before running the next set of commands. We always recommend the SSH option as it is more secure. See the following GitHub documentation before proceeding.

    If you are using Personal Access Tokens and HTTPS.

    git remote add origin https://github.com/yourusername/dummy-rust-project.git
git branch -M main
git push -u origin main

    If you are using SSH for your Git credentials.

    git remote add origin git@github.com:yourusername/dummy-rust-project.git
git branch -M main
git push -u origin main

    Once successfully pushed to your remote repository, you will see an orange or yellow circle next to your commit message. That means the CI is running. Clicking it will give you a slightly detailed status similar to the screenshot below.

    Once the CI completes all of its executions successfully, the color of the circle becomes green. Clicking the blue-colored text "Details" will head to the Actions webpage of a specific CI run.

    You can see in the "Run Rust binary" step, it contains the text output of "Hello, Stackie!".

    Congratulations on running your first Rust project on the CI.

  • Step 3: A Brief Explainer for the Workflow File

    The workflow file, ci.yml, is a good basic structure for running multiple commands to install, and build or run a Rust project.

    Our CI name is declared by this line.

    name: CI for Dummy Rust Project
    YAML

    Followed by an event trigger configuration.

    on: ["push", "pull_request"]
    YAML

    The event triggers are essential for the CI runners to run. If it's not declared, your CI won't run at all. The workflow file for the "dummy rust project" will run the CI if it is a git-push event or a GitHub pull request.

    Next, there is also an environmental variable key but only one environmental variable is set.

    env:
  CARGO_TERM_COLOR: always
    YAML

    This is set in the container's environment. This ensures that when cargo runs, the text will also have colors other than white or black. You can always set this to "none" or remove the "env" key entirely in the YAML file if you don't want the colors.

    You can always add additional environmental variables such as LS_COLORS or something related to Rust's environmental variables such as CARGO_HOME.

    The CI runs on a Linux distribution called Ubuntu, specifically, the latest available release of Ubuntu.

    jobs:
  build:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    YAML

    Most CI runners are capable of running a Windows image, a MacOS image, and OCI containers (those that run on docker or podman). They're not covered in this tutorial but it's technically possible.

    The last part is the execution steps.

        steps:
    - name: Checkout
      uses: actions/checkout@v4
    - name: Install Rustup and Rust
      run: |
        sudo apt update
        sudo apt upgrade -y
        sudo apt install rustup -y
        rustup install stable
    - name: Run Rust binary
      run: |
        cargo run
    YAML

    The first step is to clone the repository into our image via the actions/checkout@v4 plugin.

    The second step is to install rustup and Rust. Since it is a Debian-based or Ubuntu-based Linux distribution, the commands to run first is the system package manager, apt. The package manager is used to update the system which ensures that packages are up-to-date and install rustup. Rustup is then used to install the latest stable version of the Rust toolchain which includes rustc, cargo, clippy, and rustfmt.

    The last step is to run the project, simply by just running cargo run.

    In the next steps, you are going to modify the code to know what it's like to have:

    - Code format checks.

    - Running tests.

    - Inconsistent and suspicious Rust code.

  • Step 4: Running Clippy, Formatting Checks and Tests in GitHub Actions

    Rust's cargo has three other subcommands that can be used to be run on the CI. These are clippy, fmt (or rustfmt), and test.

    Clippy is Rust's linter. It checks for code inconsistencies and weird logic that might affect your code e.g. optimisation impacts caused by using the last method for a double ended iterator.

    fmt or rustfmt is Rust's code formatter. With the --check flag, it helps check if you follow formatting conventions without changing or modifying your code.

    test is another cargo subcommand. It runs the tests declared in your Rust code. It's always recommended to run tests in the CI.

    Edit the code for main.rs and replace its contents with the following code.

    use dummy_rust_project::hello;

fn main() {
    let unused_var: i32;
    let say_hello = hello("Stackie");
    println!("{}", say_hello);
}
    Rust

    Save the file. Edit your workflow file ci.yml located at .github/workflows. It should look like the code below.

    name: CI for Dummy Rust Project

on: ["push", "pull_request"]

env:
  CARGO_TERM_COLOR: always

jobs:
  build:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    steps:
    - name: Checkout
      uses: actions/checkout@v4
    - name: Install Rustup and Rust
      run: |
        sudo apt update
        sudo apt upgrade -y
        sudo apt install rustup -y
        rustup install stable
    - name: Run Rust binary
      run: |
        cargo run
    - name: Run clippy
      run: |
        cargo clippy
    YAML

    Save the file. Run the following commands at the root directory of your project.

    git add .github/workflows/ci.yml src/main.rs
git commit -m 'ci: run clippy with new code'
git push

    Head to your "dummy-rust-project" GitHub repository. Your GitHub actions will now have an extra step called "Run clippy".

    And you will get these similar compiler warning messages on both CI steps "Run Rust binary" and "Run clippy".

    You might realise that it might be best if running clippy should be done first before running the binary. It is recommended to run clippy before running tests and even a sample command e.g. to get output from an executable.

    If you are building a library in Rust, this actually makes sense and in most cases, the executable code is separated from the library code.

    Also, compilation with clippy (without the release flag) is significantly faster, allowing for the quick identification of failed checks prior to the more time-consuming and resource-intensive full compilation step.

    But since our code is not resource intensive, it's not going to affect the CI, in any way.

    Let's make this clippy run fail in the CI. Replace contents of your main.rs file with the following code.

    use dummy_rust_project::hello;

fn main() {
    let unused_var: i32;
    let say_hello = hello("Stackie");
    println!("{}", say_hello);
    let vec: Vec<isize> = Vec::new();
    if vec.len() <= 0 {}
    if 100 > i32::MAX {}
}
    Rust

    The additional code is based on the code example https://rust-lang.github.io/rust-clippy/master/index.html#absurd_extreme_comparisons.

    Running the following command cargo build will not give you an error. However, running cargo clippy does. It will tell you the reason why it fails as an error message with the link for the reason.

    Pushing the code will also cause the CI to fail and give a red colored circle with an X in the middle.

    The fix to this is to follow the code fixes suggested by clippy. Try to follow it and make the CI fully green!

    After following clippy's suggestions, run the following command.

    git add -A
git commit -m 'ci: make ci green'
git push

    It should re-run the CI and you should expect the run is green.

  • Step 5: Running Clippy, Formatting Checks and Tests in GitHub Actions (Continued)

    Let's try to use rustfmt or cargo fmt. This is Rust's code formatter and it follows conventions based on what was the most agreed upon format. Let's try to mess up the code's format like adding space here and there, putting the semi-colon too far, et cetera. Try the following code below to cause a messed up code format.

    use dummy_rust_project::hello;

fn main() {
let                        unused_var: i32;
    let say_hello =



        hello("Stackie")            ;
    println!(
        "{}",



            say_hello);
}
    Rust

    And replace your ci.yml file with the following configuration.

    name: CI for Dummy Rust Project

on: ["push", "pull_request"]

env:
  CARGO_TERM_COLOR: always

jobs:
  build:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    steps:
    - name: Checkout
      uses: actions/checkout@v4
    - name: Install Rustup and Rust
      run: |
        sudo apt update
        sudo apt upgrade -y
        sudo apt install rustup -y
        rustup install stable
    - name: Run Rust binary
      run: |
        cargo run
    - name: Run clippy
      run: |
        cargo clippy
    - name: Check format
      run: |
        cargo fmt --check
    YAML

    Save both files. Run the following commands.

    git add .github/workflows/ci.yml src/main.rs
git commit -m 'ci: check formatting'
git push

    Your CI should show red now.

    The fix for this is to run the following command on your terminal at the root directory of your project.

    cargo fmt

    Then push the new changes by running the following commands.

    git add -A
git commit -m 'format: run cargo fmt'
git push

    Your CI should be all green once the CI run finishes.

  • Step 6: Running Clippy, Formatting Checks and Tests in GitHub Actions (Continued)

    Lastly, is adding tests. Edit first src/lib.rs at the root of your project directory. Replace its contents with the following code.

    pub fn hello(name: &str) -> String {
    let hello_string = format!("Hello, {}!", name);
    hello_string
}

pub fn goodbye(name: &str) -> String {
    let goodbye_string = format!("Goodbye, {}!", name);
    goodbye_string
}

#[cfg(test)]
mod tests {
    use super::*;
    #[test]
    fn hello_stackie_matches() {
        let hello_string = hello("Stackie");
        assert_eq!("Hello, Stackie!", &hello_string)
    }

    #[test]
    fn goodbye_stackie_matches() {
        let goodbye_string = goodbye("Stackie");
        assert_eq!("Goodbye, Stackie!", &goodbye_string)
    }
}
    Rust

    What was added is an additional tests module with the #[cfg(test)] attribute. Inside the tests module, is an import of the current crate using super. Each function in the tests module are test functions because they are supplied with a #[test] attribute.

    Running the following command should give you passed tests.

    cargo test

    Now, try changing "Hello, Stackie!" to "Hello, Stacker!" within double quotes. Running the following command

    cargo test

    should at least fail one of the tests.

    Of course, although running tests can be done manually, huge codebases tend to let the CI runners to run the tests themselves e.g. after pushing new code changes.

    In the ci.yml file, append a new step. Copy the configuration below and replace the previous contents of your workflow file.

    name: CI for Dummy Rust Project

on: ["push", "pull_request"]

env:
  CARGO_TERM_COLOR: always

jobs:
  build:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    steps:
    - name: Checkout
      uses: actions/checkout@v4
    - name: Install Rustup and Rust
      run: |
        sudo apt update
        sudo apt upgrade -y
        sudo apt install rustup -y
        rustup install stable
    - name: Run Rust binary
      run: |
        cargo run
    - name: Run clippy
      run: |
        cargo clippy
    - name: Check format
      run: |
        cargo fmt --check
    - name: Run tests
      run: |
        cargo test
    YAML

    Run the following commands.

    cargo fmt
git add .github/workflows/ci.yml src/lib.rs
git commit -m 'ci: add tests'
git push

    Your CI should fail on the "Run tests" step. Of course, to fix that, you will have to revert the "Hello, Stacker!" string back to "Hello, Stackie!". Fix it and try pushing a new change again to your remote repository to make the CI full green status.

  • Step 7: Stacking It Up!

    Congratulations on finishing this short tutorial! You have learned the basics on how to add CI to your Rust projects. However, you might have some questions regarding what's the best CI configuration for Rust projects. You can check out any kind of Rust project in GitHub and read their CI workflow files. You can start by running the following search query on GitHub using this link: https://github.com/search?q=language%3Arust&type=repositories.

    If you have other questions and suggestions in improving this tutorial, feel free to send your feedback in our Discord server!
